{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.08,0.07,0.02,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5261"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82814"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6512"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43352"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the emergency department with chest pain and shortness of breath that started the previous evening. His chest pain is on the right side of the chest, stabbing in quality, and increases with inspiration. He is short of breath even at rest. He denies any preceding traumatic event or over exertion. He reports no fevers, chills, or sputum production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). He has a 35-pack-year smoking history and is taking tiotropium each morning and salbutamol on an as-needed basis, usually about twice per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his temperature is 36.7 \u00b0C, blood pressure 130/80mmHg, pulse 115/min, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 84% on room air. He has absent breath sounds in the right upper lung field. He has a minimal end-expiratory wheeze bi basally, with no crackles. His heart sounds are dual, with no murmurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is 188 cm tall and weighs 79 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is performed (Image):\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following treatments do you think is likely to contribute most to his recovery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insertion of a chest tube","Administration of salbutamol-ipratropium nebuliser","Administration of prednisone","Administration of azithromycin","Non-invasive ventilation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe above patient is presenting with a symptomatic pneumothorax (absent breath sounds on the right side of the chest), likely from a bleb rupture related to his underlying COPD. The chest X-ray shows right lung collapse with a 20% pneumothorax. The partial collapse can be seen at the apex and the right base. This can lead to severe respiratory distress and cardiovascular collapse if not treated promptly\u003Cstrong\u003E. A chest tube insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment to relieve the pressure and allow his lung to re-expand. Supplemental oxygen and needle decompression are appropriate urgent measures to stabilise the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g., continuous positive airway pressure or bilevel positive airway pressure) is a treatment option for respiratory support in certain cases, such as acute exacerbations of COPD with respiratory failure. While the patient has COPD, the primary concern in this case is the potential pneumothorax causing significant respiratory compromise. In the presence of a pneumothorax, non-invasive ventilation may not be sufficient, and the insertion of a chest tube is more appropriate for managing this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of an salbutamol-ipratropium nebuliser\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in the management of the patient\u0027s COPD, but his current symptoms are related to his pneumothorax. Nebulisers are not appropriate in the acute management of a pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of prednisone\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in the management of COPD exacerbation, but his current symptoms are related to his pneumothorax. Prednisolone is not appropriate in the acute management of a pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as there is no suggestion of infection in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common symptoms of pneumothorax are chest pain and shortness of breath.","Secondary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs in the presence of underlying lung disease, primarily chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Supplemental oxygen would be appropriate followed by needle aspiration or chest tube insertion to remove air from the pleural space."],"references":["McKnight CL, Burns B. Pneumothorax. [Updated 2023 Feb 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-","Roberts ME, Rahman NM, Maskell NA, et al; BTS Pleural Guideline Development Group. British Thoracic Society Guideline for pleural disease. Thorax. 2023 Jul;78(Suppl 3):s1-s42. doi: 10.1136/thorax-2022-219784. PMID: 37433578. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37433578/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82814"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20074"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20074"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dce7279e-a8d2-4e78-b0f4-522cc1af7a43.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dce7279e-a8d2-4e78-b0f4-522cc1af7a43.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":718,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82814"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T17:09:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25T17:10:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5261"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"